    "crumb": "Course Booklet",
    "text": "IIT Bombay follows a specialized credit-based semester system, therefore registration at the beginning of each semester is mandatory for you till you complete your program (lookout for the dates in the Academic Calendar ). Without registration, any academic activity (course/seminar/project, etc.) that you undergo will not be counted towards the requirements of your degree. 1.1 &nbsp;Pre-Registration When: Usually held about a week before the official course registration begins. This year's dates are 10th July, 2026 - 14th July, 2026 for the Autumn Semester and 12th December, 2026 - 16th December, 2026 for the Spring Semester. Note that Pre-registration is NOT FCFS (First-Come-First-Serve). What it covers: Minor Courses, Popular and high-demand electives (e.g., Entrepreneurship electives) and certain specific department electives. Process for minor registration pre-registration can be found here How allocation works: Most minor courses are generally allocated based on CPI, and some others are allotted on the professor's selection criteria. Where to pre-register: Through the External ASC portal under the Forms/Requests section. Click here for a guide video for the same. Prerequisites: Semester fees must be paid and at least the first SMA instalment should be cleared via External ASC. 1.2 &nbsp;Registration When: Happens before the start of each semester, at the end of December for the Spring Semester and end of July for the Autumn Semester. Autumn Semester: 21st July, 2026 - 24th July, 2026 Spring Semester: 29th December, 2026 - 1st January, 2027 Where to register: Use the Internal ASC portal → go to Academics → Registration → Registration/Adjustments. Click here for a guide video for the same. How it works: Courses you’ve already pre-registered for (like electives and minors) will be automatically added. You can also register for additional courses (not part of pre-registration) or any pre-reg courses that still have open slots. These open courses are allotted on a First-Come-First-Serve (FCFS) basis, so early action is advised. Important Reminders: You must register for the semester on internal ASC before the final deadline mentioned in the Academic Calendar. Once submitted successfully, you’ll receive a confirmation email. Missing the registration submission can result in your registration not being processed, so don’t wait till the last moment! 1.3 &nbsp;Course Adjustment Duration: Typically open for around 7-10 days after the course registration period ends. The last date for course adjustment this year is: Autumn Semester: 3rd August 2026 Spring Semester: 11th January 2027 What you can do: Add or remove courses (generally electives, for core courses - you need the permission of your FacAd). You can make multiple changes during this phase, but must re-submit the updated course registration form each time you make the changes. Conditions: Your total credits should not fall below 18 or exceed the overload limit as per your category. 1.4 &nbsp;Dropping of Courses If a student finds their academic load too heavy, even after the date for course adjustment has passed, they may drop some courses out of the registered ones provided the minimum credit limit for a semester (18 credits) holds. Dropping core courses requires prior consultation with your Faculty Advisor. This year the dates are for the Autumn Semester: First half-semester courses: 4th August, 2026 - 17th August, 2026 Second half-semester courses: 21st September, 2026 - 12th October, 2026 Full-semester courses: 4th August, 2026 - 17th August, 2026 Spring Semester: First half-semester courses: 12th January, 2027 - 25th January, 2027 Second half-semester courses: 1st March, 2027 - 22nd March, 2027 Full-semester courses: 12th January, 2027 - 25th January, 2027 1.5 &nbsp;Semester Wise Courses Offered You can check a particular semester’s curriculum on ASC. Follow the path: Academic --&gt; All about courses --&gt; Curriculum. Kindly note: From the third semester onwards, registration is dependent on the Academic Standing of the student"
