    "id": "academic-standing",
    "page": "content",
    "title": "Academic Standing",
    "crumb": "Course Booklet",
    "text": "At the end of every semester, every student is assigned an Academic Standing (Category I&ndash;VI) based on their academic performance over the previous two regular registered semesters. Your academic standing determines the maximum number of credits you can register for in the upcoming semester. Note: An NP (Not Passed) grade in a non-credited course is not treated as a failed course (FR/DX/DR/W) for determining academic standing. Categories of Academic Standing Category Eligibility Implication I A student who has no FR/DX/DR/W in any of the core courses, and has a CPI equal to or greater than 8.0. Upto 54 credits II CPI &lt; 8. Registered for at least 18 credits in each of the two preceding regular semesters and not failed in any course in these two semesters. Upto 48 credits III Received at least 1 FR/DX/W/DR in core courses and at most 1 FR/DX in other courses in the previous two semesters. Upto 48 credits IV Received at least 1 FR/DX/W/DR in core courses and more than one FR/DX in other courses in the previous two semesters. Upto 48 credits V Not earned at least 18 credits in either one of the previous two regular registered semesters. Upto 36 credits VI Accumulated at least 36 credits worth of FR/DX in core courses. Upto 24 credits Note: Academic Standing is recalculated before every semester registration based on your performance in the previous two regular registered semesters. Category VI supersedes all other categories. If you satisfy the conditions for Category VI, you will be placed in Category VI regardless of any other category. Students in the 8th semester of B.Tech./B.S. and 10th semester of Dual Degree programmes may be permitted to register for up to 54 credits with the recommendation of their Faculty Advisor/PIC, subject to Institute rules. If your grades from an exchange semester are not available before registration, your Academic Standing is determined using the last two completed semesters. For more details, please refer to the Institute Academic Rulebook."
